2026-02-27T19:10:41.7988538Z       "body": "This PR addresses the case where a parameter is optional but has a default that is not `None`, and the user wishes to detect that a `null` value was passed, versus the value not being defined at all.\r\n\r\n### Use case\r\n\r\nThis is an example of a use case for which this behavior is crucial:\r\n```python\r\n@app.patch('/users/{user_id}')\r\ndef edit_user(user_id: int, name: str | None = None, organization_id: int | None = -1):\r\n    # user_id is the ID of a user in the database\r\n    user = lookup_user(user_id)\r\n    # If a name was given, save the user's name\r\n    if name is not None:\r\n        user.name = name\r\n    # If an organization id was given, edit the organization to which the user belongs\r\n    # If organization_id is -1, we know that no value has been received\r\n    if organization_id != -1:\r\n        # The user might not belong to any organization and we want to handle that case\r\n        if organization_id is not None:\r\n            lookup_organization(organization_id)\r\n        user.organization_id = organization_id # int | None\r\n    save_user(user)\r\n    return {\"success\": True}\r\n```\r\n\r\n### Previous behavior\r\n\r\n```\r\nPATCH /users/123\r\n{}\r\n```\r\nwould result in `organization_id == -1` (as expected), but:\r\n```\r\nPATCH /users/123\r\n{\r\n  \"organization_id\": null\r\n}\r\n```\r\nwould also result in `organization_id == -1`, which provides no way to distinguish the two.\r\n\r\n### New behavior\r\n\r\n```\r\nPATCH /users/123\r\n{}\r\n```\r\nresults in `organization_id == -1` (as before), but:\r\n```\r\nPATCH /users/123\r\n{\r\n  \"organization_id\": null\r\n}\r\n```\r\nnow results in `organization_id is None`.\r\n\r\n### Additional comments\r\n\r\nResolves #6058 and #1661 .\r\n\r\nTests included, all tests passing.\r\n",
